Below is my step‐by‐step reasoning and the final formal specification:

Step‐by‐step reasoning:
• A key psychological mechanism is fairness evaluation: responders compare the monetary offer (split_self) with what they believe is “fair” given the contributions. In this task, fairness can be defined proportionally, so that a fair share equals the participant’s contribution relative to the total tokens available multiplied by the combined monetary pot.
• In line with inequity aversion principles, any deviation from this fair share leads to a “penalty” on utility. However, people may be more sensitive either to being under‐paid (disadvantageous inequality) or to having extra compared to fairness (advantageous inequality) – these two sensitivities can be captured with two separate parameters. This allows us to capture asymmetries in social preferences.
• Mathematically, we calculate a fair share as:
  fair_share = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) × combined_earning.
• The utility for accepting a proposal is then given by the monetary benefit (split_self) reduced by the penalties proportional to the deviation from fairness: if the offer is less than fair, a penalty weighted by alpha_param applies; if the offer exceeds fair share, a penalty weighted by beta_param applies.
• Our single equation incorporates the data variables (split_self, token_self, token_opp, combined_earning) into a fairness comparison, using two learnable parameters (alpha_param and beta_param) that are each bounded within a generous finite range. These parameters can then be calibrated using the data.
• The model predicts only responder behavior and does not incorporate additional parameters for decision stochasticity.

Below is the formal mathematical specification and variable descriptions.

<MODEL>
Let F = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) × combined_earning
U_accept = split_self − alpha_param × max(F − split_self, 0) − beta_param × max(split_self − F, 0)
</MODEL>

